**Sec. 90001. Border infrastructure and wall system.**
The Commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection receives $46.55 billion for fiscal year 2025 to construct, install, or improve primary, waterborne, and secondary barriers, access roads, and detection technology like cameras and sensors. These funds remain available until September 30, 2029, and cover necessary ground preparation work to enable U.S. Customs and Border Protection operations. The appropriation is drawn from unappropriated Treasury funds to support the physical expansion of the border wall system.

**Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection personnel, fleet vehicles, and facilities.**
U.S. Customs and Border Protection is appropriated $11.9 billion for fiscal year 2025 to hire and train agents, provide retention bonuses, repair or acquire patrol vehicles, and construct or lease facilities. Specifically, $4.1 billion is allocated for personnel hiring and training, $2.05 billion for bonuses, $855 million for vehicles, and $5 billion for facilities, all available until September 30, 2029. A restriction prohibits using these funds to recruit or train processing coordinators after October 31, 2028.

**Sec. 90003. Detention capacity.**
U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement receives $45 billion for fiscal year 2025 to expand single adult alien detention capacity and family residential center capacity, with funds available until September 30, 2029. Aliens may be detained in family residential centers pending removal decisions or until removal is executed, while detention standards for single adults are set at the discretion of the Secretary of Homeland Security. The section defines family residential centers as facilities for detaining family units, including children who are not unaccompanied alien children.

**Sec. 90004. Border security, technology, and screening.**
The Commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection is appropriated $6.168 billion for fiscal year 2025 to procure nonintrusive inspection equipment, upgrade air and marine platforms, and enhance surveillance technologies along the southwest, northern, and maritime borders. These funds support the deployment of artificial intelligence, biometric entry and exit systems, and initial screenings for unaccompanied alien children, remaining available until September 30, 2029. A restriction prohibits the procurement of untested surveillance towers that lack autonomous capabilities, defined as systems using algorithms to detect and track items without active human command.

**Sec. 90005. State and local assistance.**
The Federal Emergency Management Agency receives $2.575 billion for fiscal year 2025 to fund state and local security capabilities, including $500 million for unmanned aircraft system detection, $625 million for the 2026 FIFA World Cup, $1 billion for the 2028 Olympics, and $450 million for the Operation Stonegarden Grant Program. Additionally, the State Border Security Reinforcement Fund is established with $10 billion to provide grants to states and local governments for border wall construction, ground preparation, and alien relocation, available until September 30, 2034. States must apply within 90 days of enactment, and the funds cannot be used to exercise immigration authorities reserved exclusively to the Federal Government.

**Sec. 90006. Presidential residence protection.**
The Federal Emergency Management Agency is appropriated $300 million for fiscal year 2025 to reimburse state and local agencies for extraordinary law enforcement costs associated with protecting designated non-governmental residences of the President. These funds cover costs incurred on or after July 1, 2024, that are directly attributable to Secret Service protection requests and exceed typical operational costs. The Federal Emergency Management Agency may use up to 3 percent of these funds for administration, and the reimbursement applies only to activities certified as requested by the Secret Service.

**Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security appropriations for border support.**
The Secretary of Homeland Security receives $10 billion for fiscal year 2025 to reimburse costs incurred in undertaking activities supporting the Department's mission to safeguard the United States borders. These funds are drawn from unappropriated Treasury money and remain available until September 30, 2029. This appropriation serves as a general support fund for border security operations beyond the specific line items detailed in previous sections.

**Sec. 90101. FEHB improvements.**
The Director of the Office of Personnel Management must implement regulations to verify the eligibility of family members added to the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program and conduct a comprehensive audit of family member coverage over a three-year period. The Director is also required to develop a process to disenroll ineligible individuals within 180 days of enactment and include fraud risk assessments for ineligible enrollees. To fund these oversight activities, $66 million is appropriated for fiscal year 2026, available until the end of fiscal year 2035, and set-aside amounts for administrative services are exempt from annual congressional limitations.

**Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.**
The Pandemic Response Accountability Committee receives $88 million for fiscal year 2026 to support oversight of the Coronavirus response and funds provided in this Act or other pandemic-related legislation, with funds remaining available until expended. The CARES Act is amended to include this reconciliation act as a covered program for the Committee and extends the Committee's authority from 2025 to 2034. This funding ensures continued federal accountability for pandemic-related expenditures.

**Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.**
The Office of Management and Budget is appropriated $100 million for fiscal year 2025 to find budget and accounting efficiencies within the executive branch. These funds are drawn from unappropriated Treasury money and remain available until September 30, 2029. The appropriation is intended to support the Office's mission to improve fiscal management across federal agencies. [end of text]


